title: 3D Programming in Java
author: Daniel Selman
description: Java 3D is a client−side Java application programming interface (API) developed at Sun Microsystems for rendering interactive 3D graphics using Java. Using Java 3D you will be able to develop richly interactive 3D applications, ranging from immersive games to scientific visualization applications.

title: Bleeding at the Keyboard: A Guide to Modern Programming with Java
author: n/a
description: Bleeding at the Keyboard made its first appearance as a material developed for the Fall 1999 C212 class at Indiana University, Bloomington. In this book, Rawlins try to guide us step by step on learning Java with the analogy of theatrical performance. Here we have objects (actors), classes (roles the actors play), methods (scenes the actors play out), Java interpreter (stage managers and producers), programmers (screenwriters and directors) and user (audiences).

title: Mastering Enterprise JavaBeans, 2nd Edition
author: John Wiley & Sons
description: Covers everything needed to start in EJB development, from the basics of EJB architecture to developing transactional, scalable, and secure multiuser enterprise applications.

title: Open Data Structures (in Java)
author: University of British Columbia Press
description: Open Data Structures covers the implementation and analysis of data structures for sequences (lists), queues, priority queues, unordered dictionaries, ordered dictionaries, and graphs.

title: Processing XML with Java
author: Addison-Wesley Professional
description: A complete tutorial over 1000 pages about writing Java programs that read and write XML documents.

title: Securing Java: Getting Down to Business with Mobile Code
author: John Wiley & Sons
description: Helps the reader to separate fact from fiction when it comes to mobile code security from throughout the entire Java range.
